{
  "query": "What are the documented effects of modifying fishing trap or pot configurations on marine fish?",
  "relevant_summary": "Documented effects of modifying fishing trap or pot configurations on marine fish include both positive outcomes for fish populations and selective improvements in fishing efficiency. According to 23 studies examining these modifications, the primary benefits are reductions in unwanted catch and improved size-selectivity. Specifically, 16 of 20 replicated studies found that various trap modifications (including different trap types, increased mesh sizes, and escape devices) significantly reduced unwanted catches of multiple fish species including brown trout, black sea bass, herring, cod, whitefish, American eel, winter flounder, and various shark/ray species. These modifications also lowered the number of unwanted species caught overall. Three of four studies demonstrated that traps or pots modified with square mesh escape windows or larger mesh sizes improved size-selectivity for species like Atlantic cod, black sea bass, and most fish species, allowing smaller fish to escape capture. However, not all modifications were universally effective - three studies found no effect on unwanted catches of certain species like white croaker, non-commercial fish, or undersized Atlantic cod, and one study actually reported increased non-target haddock catches. Importantly, one study found that survival rates of small herring that escaped through size-sorting grids were similar to trap-caught herring that did not pass through grids, indicating that escape mechanisms do not necessarily harm fish survival.",
