  "relevant_summary": "In European waters, the evidence shows that square mesh codends are generally more effective than diamond mesh codends for reducing unwanted catch. Based on 26 studies, 10 out of 16 replicated, controlled studies found that square mesh codends reduced unwanted catches of all fish species monitored, young individuals of commercially targeted fish, total unwanted catch (fish and invertebrates), and discarded fish in deeper fishing areas. Studies conducted in European waters including the English Channel, Mediterranean Sea, North Sea (Kattegat and Skagerrak), Adriatic Sea, and Atlantic Ocean demonstrate these benefits. Additionally, 6 out of 14 studies found that square mesh codends improved size selectivity for several commercially important species including silver hake, horse mackerel, European hake, axillary seabream, poor cod, greater forkbeard, and blue whiting. However, effectiveness varied by species, with some studies finding no difference in selectivity for certain species like Atlantic mackerel and long rough dab, or finding that effectiveness depended on fish body shape (improved for roundfish but not flatfish). One study also found that square mesh codends reduced non-commercial unwanted invertebrates in at least one of two areas tested in the English Channel.",
